1
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:14,800
[Epic Western music]

2
00:02:01,400 --> 00:02:03,400
[Cows mooing]

3
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:08,000
[Lively instrumental music]

4
00:03:10,200 --> 00:03:12,200
[Music slows]

5
00:03:38,600 --> 00:03:40,600
[Cheerful instrumental music]

6
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:54,200
[Dogs barking]

7
00:04:01,600 --> 00:04:02,600
DR. LYNNTON: There he is.

8
00:04:02,800 --> 00:04:05,200
There's the stallion. That's War Winds.

9
00:04:08,600 --> 00:04:09,600
Beautiful.

10
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:12,200
That's my daughter riding him. Leslie.

11
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:20,200
Leslie is my daughter. She's riding him.

12
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:24,800
Doctor, that sure is a beautiful animal.

13
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,600
DR. LYNNTON: We'll get to the horses
in the morning.

14
00:04:28,600 --> 00:04:31,600
<i>Now you'll come up to the house</i>
<i>and get ready for dinner.</i>

15
00:04:37,400 --> 00:04:40,000
[Soft instrumental music]

16
00:04:51,400 --> 00:04:53,600
You're from Nevada, Mr. Beckwith?

17
00:04:54,800 --> 00:04:56,000
Texas, Mama.

18
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
MRS. LYNNTON: You from Texas,
Mr. Beckwith?

19
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,800
BICK: Yes, ma'am, Texas.
Benedict's the name.

20
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:05,000
MRS. LYNNTON: You're here
about the horses, aren't you?

21
00:05:05,200 --> 00:05:06,000
BICK: Yes, ma'am.

22
00:05:06,800 --> 00:05:11,200
I came to buy your stallion, War Winds,
if your daughter doesn't mind too much.

23
00:05:12,800 --> 00:05:16,200
In all likelihood,
Leslie will be leaving us soon anyway.

24
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:22,800
David is with the embassy in Washington.
He's been called back to England.

25
00:05:23,600 --> 00:05:25,600
Will she like it there, do you think?

26
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:29,400
She's going to marry him?

27
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:34,200
Mother! Let me sell Mr. Benedict
War Winds.

28
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:37,000
I can tell you all his bad points.

29
00:05:37,600 --> 00:05:40,200
For one, he eats too much,
doesn't he, Papa?

30
00:05:40,800 --> 00:05:44,400
You see, it's either War Winds or me.
Something has to go.

31
00:05:44,600 --> 00:05:48,200
You know that horse is just too spirited
for any woman to ride.

32
00:05:48,600 --> 00:05:53,600
I know your horse is going to miss you
and all this nice, green country, but...

33
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,400
I'll try to make him happy in Texas.

34
00:05:56,400 --> 00:05:58,600
Isn't Texas green, Mr. Benedict?

35
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:01,200
No, ma'am, not altogether.

36
00:06:01,600 --> 00:06:04,200
MRS. LYNNTON: You must tell us
about Texas, Mr. Benedict.

37
00:06:04,600 --> 00:06:06,200
BICK: It's not that easy.

38
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,600
It's different than any other state, I think.

39
00:06:13,400 --> 00:06:17,000
At least that's what we think.
It's almost a different country.

40
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:22,200
DAVID: From an Englishman's point
of view, its size takes your breath away.

41
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:24,200
Yes, it's big all right.

42
00:06:24,400 --> 00:06:26,200
How large are your ranches?

43
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,400
Most every size. Large and small.

44
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,200
Mr. Benedict's Reata is
one of the largest of them all.

45
00:06:33,600 --> 00:06:34,800
Oh, really?

46
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,000
And just how large is that?

47
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:40,200
It's one of the biggest.

48
00:06:42,800 --> 00:06:44,000
How big is that?

49
00:06:45,200 --> 00:06:49,600
There are one or two others as big,
I suppose, up where we come from...

50
00:06:50,600 --> 00:06:53,200
and some larger ones on the coastal plains.

51
00:06:54,600 --> 00:06:56,800
Can't you be more specific?

52
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:00,800
What's the size of your place?
50,000? 20,000 acres?

53
00:07:06,600 --> 00:07:10,600
Around a half million.
595,000 acres, to be exact.

54
00:07:12,200 --> 00:07:14,200
I'd call that quite a parcel!

55
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:16,800
How many acres did you say, Mr. Benedict?

56
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:20,400
He said 595,000 acres, Mama.

57
00:07:20,600 --> 00:07:23,000
And you should see the greedy look
on your face.

58
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:25,000
<i>Witness excused.</i>

59
00:07:26,400 --> 00:07:29,600
<i>Won't you join us at the Hunt Ball?</i>
<i>I'm sure you'll enjoy it.</i>

60
00:07:29,800 --> 00:07:32,000
BICK: No, thank you, Miss Leslie.

61
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,600
I'm afraid I wouldn't look good
in this outfit.

62
00:07:39,400 --> 00:07:42,000
[Soft instrumental music]

63
00:07:52,400 --> 00:07:53,800
I like your country.

64
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:59,600
Why don't you stay a while
and really see something of it?

65
00:08:00,800 --> 00:08:03,600
It's roundup time in my country.
Big spring roundup.

66
00:08:05,600 --> 00:08:06,800
Your country?

67
00:08:07,200 --> 00:08:08,400
Reata.

68
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,200
Your country, my country.
You make us sound so far apart.

69
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:26,000
Maybe you could come out and see it...

70
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:28,400
if you get a chance.

71
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:47,800
BICK: Leslie....
DAVID: Leslie, dear.

72
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:50,800
BICK: Miss Leslie....
DAVID: Leslie?

73
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,800
I'll be off real early in the morning, so...

74
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:57,000
goodbye.

75
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,800
I'm awfully glad you came.

76
00:08:59,800 --> 00:09:02,600
I'm not going to say goodbye to you
in the moonlight.

77
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:05,400
It would just be too touching. Good night!

78
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,000
[Music swells]

79
00:09:26,600 --> 00:09:28,600
[Sentimental instrumental music]

80
00:10:20,800 --> 00:10:21,800
"Texas."

81
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:26,600
Are you in love with him?

82
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:28,400
Yes, I think so.

83
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,400
<i>Will you do me a favor</i>
<i>and run along to bed?</i>

84
00:10:41,800 --> 00:10:43,400
LACEY: Leslie?
LESLIE: Good night.

85
00:10:51,600 --> 00:10:53,800
If you won't marry David Karfrey...

86
00:10:55,200 --> 00:10:56,600
will you give him to me?

87
00:10:56,800 --> 00:10:58,400
LESLIE: Yes! Now, good night.

88
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:03,200
[Soft instrumental music]

89
00:11:25,800 --> 00:11:28,200
BICK: As far as I'm concerned, it's a deal.

90
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:35,800
DR. LYNNTON: $10,000 is a lot of money.
BICK: It's a lot of horse.

91
00:11:36,600 --> 00:11:38,800
DR. LYNNTON: Let's have some breakfast
and get going.

92
00:11:53,400 --> 00:11:55,200
BICK: Why, Leslie!
LESLIE: Good morning.

93
00:12:06,600 --> 00:12:10,000
You don't look as if you'd been dancing
all night, Miss Leslie.

94
00:12:10,800 --> 00:12:12,600
I came home at 10:45.

95
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:16,600
I read about Texas until 5:00 this morning.

96
00:12:16,600 --> 00:12:19,200
Let the poor boy eat his breakfast in peace.

97
00:12:21,800 --> 00:12:24,000
It takes a heap of reading, Texas does.

98
00:12:26,800 --> 00:12:28,800
We really stole Texas, didn't we?

99
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:31,400
<i>I mean, away from Mexico.</i>

100
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:36,600
You're catching me a bit early
to start joking.

101
00:12:36,800 --> 00:12:40,400
But I'm not joking.
It's all right there in the history books.

102
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,600
<i>Mr. Austin came down</i>
<i>with 300 families, it says.</i>

103
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:47,800
The next thing you know,
they're claiming it from Mexico.

104
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:54,800
I never heard anything as ignorant
as some Eastern people--

105
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:55,800
Oh, please, Jordan.

106
00:12:56,400 --> 00:12:59,000
<i>I'm only speaking impersonally.</i>
<i>About history.</i>

107
00:12:59,400 --> 00:13:02,000
You all think
that the glory happened in the East...

108
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:04,200
with Valley Forge and Bunker Hill!

109
00:13:05,400 --> 00:13:09,400
Do you know about San Jacinto?
Have you heard about the Alamo?

110
00:13:09,800 --> 00:13:11,200
Why, certainly.

111
00:13:12,400 --> 00:13:14,600
I read about them all last night.

112
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:20,200
I didn't mean to be impolite,
but it's so new to me.

113
00:13:21,400 --> 00:13:23,400
<i>I just mean, it's just all so new...</i>

114
00:13:24,200 --> 00:13:25,800
and so fascinating!

115
00:13:26,200 --> 00:13:30,600
You mustn't talk that way to a Texan.
They feel very strongly about their state.

116
00:13:30,800 --> 00:13:32,800
He shouldn't take it so hard.

117
00:13:34,400 --> 00:13:38,400
Jordan, you would think
somebody had spoiled you terribly.

118
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:40,400
Your wife or somebody.

119
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:44,600
I haven't any wife. I live with my sister.

120
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:54,400
Why aren't you married?

121
00:13:56,200 --> 00:14:00,600
First you attack a man's country,
and now you try to pry into his family life.

122
00:14:01,400 --> 00:14:02,400
Thank you, Doctor.

123
00:14:05,400 --> 00:14:06,800
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

124
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:09,400
-Good morning, Lacey.
-Good morning, Papa.

125
00:14:11,800 --> 00:14:13,000
How are we doing?

126
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:16,800
We'll have to be getting along soon
if you're going to make your train.

127
00:14:20,200 --> 00:14:23,200
-Good morning, everybody.
-Good morning, Nancy.

128
00:14:23,800 --> 00:14:24,800
Good morning, dear.

129
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:26,600
Good morning, Mr. Benedict.

130
00:14:26,800 --> 00:14:29,000
Isn't this a beautiful morning?

131
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:43,200
Leslie, if Mr. Benedict has finished
his breakfast...

132
00:14:43,400 --> 00:14:45,400
why don't you show him the stables?

133
00:14:45,800 --> 00:14:50,200
We've just quarreled politely about Texas.
It's no use trying to pawn me off on him.

134
00:14:53,400 --> 00:14:54,600
[Whispering] And anyway, Mother...

135
00:14:54,800 --> 00:14:58,600
he's probably engaged to marry
the daughter of the adjoining ranch...

136
00:14:59,200 --> 00:15:02,000
who, though beautiful,
is comparatively poor.

137
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:05,400
She only has 200,000 acres
and half a million cows.

138
00:15:07,800 --> 00:15:09,800
Is she pretty?

139
00:15:13,800 --> 00:15:15,000
We must hurry.

140
00:15:17,400 --> 00:15:20,000
<i>Mr. Benedict and I will have</i>
<i>to be leaving now.</i>

141
00:15:21,800 --> 00:15:23,800
<i>Goodbye, everybody.</i>

142
00:15:34,800 --> 00:15:36,000
<i>Benedict!</i>

143
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:39,800
Who, may I ask, is the lucky young lady
that you're going to marry...

144
00:15:40,200 --> 00:15:42,000
with all those cows?

145
00:15:44,400 --> 00:15:45,600
DR. LYNNTON: I'll get the car.

146
00:15:48,600 --> 00:15:52,400
It's funny, ma'am.
My neighbor is a girl, Vashti Hake.

147
00:16:02,200 --> 00:16:05,200
There was some talk of my marrying her,
but I'm not.

148
00:16:05,400 --> 00:16:07,800
DR. LYNNTON: Come on,
if you want to catch that train.

149
00:16:10,800 --> 00:16:12,800
It all sounds so romantic!

150
00:16:16,200 --> 00:16:19,000
[Sentimental instrumental music]

151
00:16:43,200 --> 00:16:44,600
[Train whistle blows]

152
00:16:51,800 --> 00:16:54,000
Come along, David, you're for me.

153
00:16:57,200 --> 00:16:59,200
[Instrumental music swells]

154
00:17:44,400 --> 00:17:46,000
LESLIE: What's that, a wolf?.

155
00:17:46,400 --> 00:17:47,600
No, honey.

156
00:17:48,800 --> 00:17:50,400
It's just a little old coyote.

157
00:17:57,600 --> 00:18:00,400
Don't you think you've done
enough sightseeing?

158
00:18:00,600 --> 00:18:02,200
LESLIE: Tell me when we're in Texas.

159
00:18:02,200 --> 00:18:04,800
BICK: That's Texas you've been looking at.

160
00:18:07,800 --> 00:18:09,400
<i>For the last eight hours.</i>

161
00:18:12,600 --> 00:18:16,400
I don't know how other brides feel
on their honeymoon...

162
00:18:17,400 --> 00:18:19,600
but I'm having a lovely time.

163
00:18:20,200 --> 00:18:22,200
We can't say it's been dull.

164
00:18:23,200 --> 00:18:25,400
That is, so far anyway.

165
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:48,200
BICK: Wake up, honey. We're here, honey.

166
00:18:51,800 --> 00:18:52,800
LESLIE: Where?

167
00:18:58,000 --> 00:18:59,000
Hello.

168
00:18:59,600 --> 00:19:00,600
Good morning.

169
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:07,400
LESLIE: Is that Texas?

170
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,000
BICK: It's Benedict.
That's where we ship from.

171
00:19:33,400 --> 00:19:35,800
[Bick speaks in Spanish]

172
00:19:47,200 --> 00:19:49,000
BICK: These people never learn!

173
00:19:51,400 --> 00:19:53,000
I'm Mrs. Benedict.

174
00:19:53,400 --> 00:19:54,800
[Responds in Spanish]

175
00:20:01,400 --> 00:20:03,600
That means, "Welcome, the newlyweds."

176
00:20:05,600 --> 00:20:07,600
[Thanks him in Spanish]

177
00:20:08,400 --> 00:20:09,600
BICK: Let's go, Leslie.

178
00:20:10,200 --> 00:20:12,000
And what is your name?

179
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:14,600
Ángel Obregón.

180
00:20:15,200 --> 00:20:17,000
That's a beautiful name.

181
00:20:19,800 --> 00:20:21,400
Come on, it's 50 miles to coffee.

182
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:23,600
[Epic instrumental music]

183
00:21:15,800 --> 00:21:18,400
This is it, honey. This is your home.

184
00:21:19,800 --> 00:21:21,400
But it's huge!

185
00:21:22,400 --> 00:21:24,600
<i>I thought it was a ranch house.</i>

186
00:21:24,600 --> 00:21:29,200
BICK: My dad built it to show the cotton
crowd we were just as high-powered.

187
00:21:29,800 --> 00:21:32,000
LESLIE: It's enormous
just for the two of us.

188
00:21:32,200 --> 00:21:33,800
BICK: Luz lives here with me.

189
00:21:34,200 --> 00:21:35,200
<i>With us.</i>

190
00:21:35,600 --> 00:21:39,800
<i>She's run the house since Ma passed on.</i>
<i>Some say she even runs the ranch!</i>

191
00:21:41,200 --> 00:21:42,600
[Bick speaks in Spanish]

192
00:21:49,200 --> 00:21:50,400
Take it easy, Leslie.

193
00:21:50,600 --> 00:21:52,000
What are your names?

194
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:53,400
[Servants answer her]

195
00:21:57,600 --> 00:21:59,200
[Leslie thanks them in Spanish]

196
00:22:08,800 --> 00:22:10,200
What do you mean behave?

197
00:22:10,600 --> 00:22:14,800
Here we don't make a fuss
over those people. You're a Texan now.

198
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:22,000
LESLIE: Is that a state of mind?
I'm still myself.

199
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:25,800
You're my wife, honey. You're a Benedict.

200
00:22:26,400 --> 00:22:30,800
LESLIE: I still have a mind of my own.
Elsewhere, being gracious is acceptable.

201
00:22:32,600 --> 00:22:34,000
We're gracious, but....

202
00:22:41,200 --> 00:22:42,600
LESLIE: Fine thing...

203
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:46,600
standing here quarreling
with rice still in our hair!

204
00:23:15,600 --> 00:23:17,800
LESLIE: It's so nice and cool!

205
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:28,200
LUZ: I thought somebody was hurt, maybe.

206
00:23:29,400 --> 00:23:31,200
We didn't know you were there.

207
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:35,800
Well, we're home. We're here.

208
00:23:36,400 --> 00:23:38,200
I've been looking for you for weeks.

209
00:23:38,800 --> 00:23:41,200
LESLIE: We weren't expected
to be back sooner, were we?

210
00:23:41,600 --> 00:23:44,600
LUZ: With all the spring work to be done,
the roundup...

211
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:47,600
I didn't figure Bick would stay away.

212
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:54,000
BICK: If I miss a roundup every time I have
a honeymoon, I won't miss much, will l?

213
00:23:54,200 --> 00:23:55,800
[Motor in distance]

214
00:24:00,600 --> 00:24:02,800
BICK: I thought I fired him off this place.

215
00:24:10,400 --> 00:24:13,200
BICK: Where do you think you're going
with my automobile?

216
00:24:13,800 --> 00:24:15,200
Just hold on.

217
00:24:15,800 --> 00:24:19,400
Don't go taking off on me.
That old truck broke down again.

218
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:26,000
You want me going down the road?

219
00:24:27,600 --> 00:24:29,400
That's exactly what I was going to do.

220
00:24:30,800 --> 00:24:33,400
But she said,
"You stay on and do your work."

221
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:35,600
BICK: Next time I say to get, you get!

222
00:24:35,600 --> 00:24:38,600
LUZ: Bick and Jett are everlasting jangling
about something.

223
00:24:39,800 --> 00:24:42,800
JETT: <i>Madama</i> is the one who said to stay.
LUZ: That's right.

224
00:24:43,600 --> 00:24:45,600
With you away,
we needed all the help there was.

225
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:50,000
They're all scared to death of her.
You know that.

226
00:24:50,800 --> 00:24:52,600
Everyone, except you and me.

227
00:24:52,800 --> 00:24:54,200
BICK: You just tend to your work.

228
00:24:54,200 --> 00:24:56,200
Tell me who is the boss around here...

229
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:01,400
and I'll be glad to do anything you want.
Just tell me who's the boss.

230
00:25:03,800 --> 00:25:05,800
This is Bick's new wife.

231
00:25:06,800 --> 00:25:09,000
Leslie, this boy here is Jett Rink.

232
00:25:09,400 --> 00:25:11,200
LESLIE: Hello.
LUZ: He works for us.

233
00:25:15,800 --> 00:25:17,800
[Western instrumental music]

234
00:25:21,400 --> 00:25:24,400
LUZ: You'd better get going, Jett,
and get that truck fixed.

235
00:25:33,200 --> 00:25:35,400
[Under his breath] Nobody is king
in this country.

236
00:25:36,600 --> 00:25:38,800
Nobody, no matter what they think.

237
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:44,800
I'm sorry, honey. Things go <i>loco</i> here
every time I'm away.

238
00:25:49,400 --> 00:25:51,800
LUZ: Remember the time of the big rodeo?

239
00:25:52,600 --> 00:25:55,800
<i>Old Kale Beebe blew in, higher than a kite...</i>

240
00:25:56,200 --> 00:25:58,600
slept on the sofa in your office.

241
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:03,400
<i>He must have had nightmares.</i>
<i>He cut the couch to ribbons with his spurs.</i>

242
00:26:04,400 --> 00:26:06,400
<i>This here is Bick's room.</i>

243
00:26:07,200 --> 00:26:09,600
<i>This down here is your room, honey.</i>

244
00:26:12,800 --> 00:26:13,800
Look....

245
00:26:16,200 --> 00:26:17,400
We're married.

246
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:20,600
You know how that is.

247
00:26:23,200 --> 00:26:25,200
<i>We'll take the connecting rooms.</i>

248
00:26:25,600 --> 00:26:29,600
<i>We'll make that into a sitting room</i>
<i>where we can sit and talk...</i>

249
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:32,400
and the breeze can get at us.

250
00:26:34,400 --> 00:26:36,000
[Loud ringing]

251
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:38,000
[Lively instrumental music]

252
00:26:42,800 --> 00:26:44,200
[Bick hooting]

253
00:27:07,800 --> 00:27:09,200
[Wind howls]

254
00:27:17,600 --> 00:27:19,000
[Luz instructs servants in Spanish]

255
00:27:22,400 --> 00:27:24,000
LUZ: Breakfast's ready.

256
00:27:25,200 --> 00:27:27,400
You and Jordan
have had breakfast already?

257
00:27:27,400 --> 00:27:31,200
We have our coffee and talk
every morning of our lives at 5:00.

258
00:27:31,600 --> 00:27:33,600
Try and get things rounded up for the day.

259
00:27:36,400 --> 00:27:39,000
I thought I was going riding with him
to the roundup.

260
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:41,800
LUZ: It would've been too hot for you.
I told him so.

261
00:27:44,200 --> 00:27:45,800
Bring it in here.

262
00:27:47,600 --> 00:27:50,400
<i>You gotta watch out for that sun.</i>
<i>It's rough.</i>

263
00:27:50,800 --> 00:27:51,600
Sit down.

264
00:27:54,400 --> 00:27:57,800
Your blood's too thin. That's the trouble
with a lot of Easterners.

265
00:28:01,600 --> 00:28:02,600
Thank you.

266
00:28:05,200 --> 00:28:06,600
I'm fine, Luz.

267
00:28:07,800 --> 00:28:10,000
I'm a lot tougher perhaps
than you think I am.

268
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:15,000
Me...

269
00:28:15,800 --> 00:28:20,000
I never had a sick day in my life.
Except when I got thrown and tromped on.

270
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:24,200
All you gotta do is take it easy.

271
00:28:24,400 --> 00:28:26,600
This rich Texas air will fix you up.

272
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,200
Don't you worry none
about being lonesome.

273
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:34,800
I'll round up the neighbors.

274
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:36,800
You're going to meet some folks.

275
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:39,600
Yes, indeed.
You're going to meet some folks.

276
00:28:42,400 --> 00:28:44,200
This is Mr. and Mrs. Bale Clinch.

277
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:47,600
Bick, it's about time. Howdy, ma'am.

278
00:28:47,600 --> 00:28:50,000
I'd like you to meet my little wife, Adarene.

279
00:28:50,200 --> 00:28:52,400
I'm mighty pleased to meet you.

280
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:55,800
This is Judge Whiteside.

281
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:59,000
How do you do, Mrs. Benedict?
We sure are proud to have you here.

282
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:02,000
Bick, congratulations.
Mighty happy for you, boy.

283
00:29:02,400 --> 00:29:03,400
She sure is pretty.

284
00:29:03,600 --> 00:29:04,800
I think so.

285
00:29:05,400 --> 00:29:06,800
LUZ: Here's Ula Japes.

286
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:08,600
Glad to meet you, ma'am.

287
00:29:08,600 --> 00:29:10,200
Good to see you, Bick.

288
00:29:10,200 --> 00:29:12,000
This is Ms. Wharton.

289
00:29:12,200 --> 00:29:14,200
Howdy, Leslie. Mighty happy to meet you.

290
00:29:15,200 --> 00:29:16,400
LUZ: Fernie Kling.

291
00:29:16,600 --> 00:29:18,800
We're glad to have you with us.

292
00:29:19,200 --> 00:29:21,400
You've really done well for yourself.

293
00:29:21,400 --> 00:29:22,600
Thank you, Fernie.

294
00:29:29,600 --> 00:29:31,800
Now you'll meet the neighbor
I told you about.

295
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:35,400
The one who lives 50 miles away
with all those cows?

296
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:39,600
Vashti, I'd like you to meet my wife.

297
00:29:40,600 --> 00:29:43,200
LESLIE: Hello, Vashti. So nice to meet you.

298
00:29:43,400 --> 00:29:45,200
Jordan told me so much about you.

299
00:29:48,400 --> 00:29:50,400
Mighty glad to know you.

300
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:52,600
I'm awfully glad we're neighbors.

301
00:29:53,200 --> 00:29:55,400
<i>I hope we'll be real close friends.</i>

302
00:30:05,600 --> 00:30:08,400
My name is Mort Snythe.
They call me Pinky.

303
00:30:11,800 --> 00:30:13,000
LUZ: Come here.

304
00:30:15,400 --> 00:30:17,600
-Excuse me, ma'am.
-We'll be seeing you.

305
00:30:17,800 --> 00:30:20,200
[Harmonica playing]

306
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:27,000
[Solemn instrumental music]

307
00:30:57,200 --> 00:30:59,800
BALE: This will perk you up.
LESLIE: Thank you.

308
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:03,800
I propose a toast to a daughter
of old Maryland...

309
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:08,400
now blooming into a citizen
of the Lone Star State. To the bride!

310
00:31:08,400 --> 00:31:09,800
[All cheering]

311
00:31:16,400 --> 00:31:17,600
Are you all right?

312
00:31:17,800 --> 00:31:19,200
I'm fine, don't worry.

313
00:31:19,600 --> 00:31:23,200
VASHTI: There's another bride here today.
BICK: How's that, Vashti?

314
00:31:24,400 --> 00:31:27,600
Mort Snythe and I were married yesterday
in Hermosa.

315
00:31:27,600 --> 00:31:29,600
[All cheering]

316
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:40,800
WOMAN: I'm gonna kiss him!

317
00:31:43,800 --> 00:31:45,600
I guess that leaves only me.

318
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:50,600
Why, Luz, everybody in the county knows
you'd rather herd cattle than make love!

319
00:31:50,600 --> 00:31:53,000
LUZ: One thing you gotta say for cattle:

320
00:31:53,600 --> 00:31:56,400
You put your brand on one of them,
you know where it's at!

321
00:32:01,200 --> 00:32:03,000
COOK: Come and get it!

322
00:32:25,200 --> 00:32:27,400
The best food you ever ate, honey.

323
00:32:27,600 --> 00:32:29,600
This is real Mexican
<i>barbacoa</i>.

324
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:32,200
That's where we get the word "barbecue."

325
00:32:38,400 --> 00:32:39,600
What is that?

326
00:32:40,800 --> 00:32:42,000
Calf's head.

327
00:32:42,800 --> 00:32:47,000
We take it and wrap it in clean white cloth
and then wrap it tight in canvas...

328
00:32:47,400 --> 00:32:50,800
and put it down in a pit
of hot mesquite coals for 18 hours.

329
00:32:50,800 --> 00:32:53,200
And do those brains taste sweet!

330
00:32:53,600 --> 00:32:54,800
How fascinating!

331
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:00,400
I don't think I'm really terribly hungry.
It must be the heat.

332
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:02,200
You call this hot?

333
00:33:02,600 --> 00:33:03,800
<i>Wait till July!</i>

334
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:08,800
Eat it while it's hot!

335
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:14,000
BALE: What's the matter with her, Bick?

336
00:33:15,800 --> 00:33:17,400
That's what I was afraid of!

337
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:24,400
[Loud ringing]

338
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:33,800
Leslie?

339
00:33:45,600 --> 00:33:46,800
LESLIE: Good morning, Luz.

340
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:50,600
What are you doing up?

341
00:33:51,400 --> 00:33:53,000
LESLIE: Getting breakfast.

342
00:33:58,200 --> 00:34:01,400
I think there's something
we should get in the clear.

343
00:34:02,400 --> 00:34:05,800
I don't want to take your place.
I want you to know that.

344
00:34:06,200 --> 00:34:09,200
But I can't have you taking my place either.

345
00:34:09,800 --> 00:34:12,800
I can't be just a guest
in my husband's house.

346
00:34:12,800 --> 00:34:14,200
BICK: There you are.

347
00:34:14,200 --> 00:34:15,600
Good morning, darling.

348
00:34:15,600 --> 00:34:17,400
BICK: How are you feeling?
LESLIE: Fine.

349
00:34:22,800 --> 00:34:24,200
You look fine.

350
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:28,800
I want everybody to know, no matter
what happens around here in the future...

351
00:34:28,800 --> 00:34:31,200
I am never going to faint again.

352
00:34:39,400 --> 00:34:42,000
I'll never get the hang of you,
Mrs. Benedict.

353
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:00,200
A horse that cost you a lot
for breeding stock, I'd use it for breeding.

354
00:35:00,400 --> 00:35:03,400
I wouldn't let anyone ride him.
I wouldn't care if she's your wife.

355
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:08,200
<i>I'd see she rides a more gentle animal</i>
<i>if I were you.</i>

356
00:35:12,600 --> 00:35:14,800
She's going to fall off and break her neck.

357
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:31,000
That's Old Polo. He's head
<i>vaquero.</i>

358
00:35:32,600 --> 00:35:34,800
He's been here longer than any of us.

359
00:35:35,200 --> 00:35:37,400
<i>Since Grandpa Benedict's time.</i>

360
00:35:48,600 --> 00:35:50,000
<i>Look at them, honey!</i>

361
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:54,800
<i>There's never been anything like them</i>
<i>in this world, l can tell you.</i>

362
00:35:55,200 --> 00:35:57,000
Did you ever see such stock?

363
00:35:58,200 --> 00:35:59,400
Are they all ours?

364
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:03,600
BICK: These and 49,000 others
just like them.

365
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:08,600
<i>Granddaddy and his boys</i>
<i>used to drive his longhorns...</i>

366
00:36:08,600 --> 00:36:11,600
great herds of them, all the way to Kansas.

367
00:36:14,600 --> 00:36:17,800
He was a pretty good old boy.
I mean, he was tough, too.

368
00:36:21,200 --> 00:36:24,400
My old man brought in stock from Europe
and bred them in the best ways.

369
00:36:24,600 --> 00:36:25,400
<i>Look out!</i>

370
00:36:29,800 --> 00:36:32,400
<i>This right here is the result, honey.</i>

371
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:34,400
Look at them.

372
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:40,600
[Jaunty instrumental music]

373
00:37:27,400 --> 00:37:28,800
How are you doing?

374
00:37:31,800 --> 00:37:32,800
Tired, honey?

375
00:37:33,200 --> 00:37:35,000
Don't you worry about me.

376
00:37:36,400 --> 00:37:38,200
I'm a tough Texan now.

377
00:37:42,600 --> 00:37:44,200
You know, I love you, Tex.

378
00:38:01,200 --> 00:38:02,600
LUZ: Howdy, everybody.

379
00:38:06,200 --> 00:38:10,000
BICK: Hold on a minute. I want you
to take Mrs. Benedict back in with you.

380
00:38:11,200 --> 00:38:13,200
<i>Go with Jett, and get out of this heat.</i>

381
00:38:13,200 --> 00:38:14,800
LESLIE: Honey, I'm fine, really.

382
00:38:14,800 --> 00:38:17,400
BICK: There's no use overdoing it.
Go along with Jett.

383
00:38:34,200 --> 00:38:35,600
Good morning, Jett.

384
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:38,200
BICK: Take it easy, Jett.

385
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:44,400
I don't want to chew on this, Bick...

386
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:47,600
but I think we'd better get it straight.

387
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:49,800
I run the house, don't l?

388
00:38:50,800 --> 00:38:52,800
Her house. Her kitchen. Her help.

389
00:38:53,600 --> 00:38:55,200
She doesn't even speak Spanish.

390
00:38:55,200 --> 00:38:57,400
They understand English
when they want to.

391
00:38:57,400 --> 00:39:00,400
I know how to handle Mexicans.
I've done it all my life.

392
00:39:01,400 --> 00:39:04,600
They'd sit on their honkers all day
if I didn't keep after them.

393
00:39:04,600 --> 00:39:06,200
All right, Luz. Cool off.

394
00:39:09,200 --> 00:39:12,200
I thought we ought to talk
without her around.

395
00:39:15,200 --> 00:39:18,400
I don't want to feel that you're setting up
against me, Bick.

396
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:25,200
Nobody is setting up against you, Luz.

397
00:39:26,400 --> 00:39:28,000
That gal's my wife.

398
00:39:29,200 --> 00:39:32,600
And you're fair enough, I think,
to try and get along with her.

399
00:39:36,600 --> 00:39:37,800
All right.

400
00:39:38,600 --> 00:39:41,400
I'll get a horse and help push
the stock along.

401
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:43,800
Maybe it'll make me feel better.

402
00:39:44,200 --> 00:39:46,000
[Under his breath]
You gotta push something.

403
00:39:46,600 --> 00:39:49,000
LUZ: When I get enough, I'll ride on in.

404
00:39:53,200 --> 00:39:55,400
JETT: Why did you come to Texas?

405
00:39:56,400 --> 00:40:00,000
I mean, everybody else's trying
to get away from here.

406
00:40:00,600 --> 00:40:03,000
Me, I'll get out of here one of these days.

407
00:40:05,200 --> 00:40:06,800
This is my husband's land.

408
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:09,400
This is his home.

409
00:40:13,600 --> 00:40:17,600
Who gets hold of this much land
unless they took it off somebody else?

410
00:40:19,200 --> 00:40:22,000
You're not exactly loyal
to your employer, Jett.

411
00:40:22,200 --> 00:40:24,400
No, I'm not complaining.

412
00:40:25,600 --> 00:40:27,600
They bought this land long ago.

413
00:40:28,200 --> 00:40:29,400
The Benedicts.

414
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:34,200
-They got it though purchase, years ago.
-Took it from some ignorant Mexicans.

415
00:40:34,200 --> 00:40:38,200
That's not true. They bought and traded
for Spanish land grants.

416
00:40:39,800 --> 00:40:43,400
They paid for it all right.
They paid five cents an acre.

417
00:40:44,600 --> 00:40:47,400
I know my folks were here long enough
to get rich, too.

418
00:40:49,600 --> 00:40:52,000
Except they just weren't so foxy.

419
00:41:09,200 --> 00:41:10,800
[Slow Western music]

420
00:41:35,600 --> 00:41:37,600
Keep it on, boy. I'll ride him.

421
00:41:39,800 --> 00:41:41,600
Nobody rides him but the
<i>señora.</i>

422
00:41:41,600 --> 00:41:44,000
I've been riding what I want to for 30 years.

423
00:41:44,400 --> 00:41:46,000
Already he bucked off López.

424
00:41:46,200 --> 00:41:49,200
If he bucks me down,
he won't be the first one that's done it.

425
00:41:51,400 --> 00:41:54,600
I suppose you came out here
to show me how to run things, too.

426
00:41:55,600 --> 00:41:56,600
Let's go.

427
00:41:57,400 --> 00:41:58,800
[War Winds neighs loudly]

428
00:42:12,800 --> 00:42:14,800
JETT: I'm not too awful bad now.

429
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:19,400
<i>I've got a few friends.</i>
<i>And "Madama" likes me.</i>

430
00:42:20,800 --> 00:42:25,000
<i>And Bick....</i>
<i>Now, even old Bick likes me a little bit.</i>

431
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:30,400
Of course,
they don't like me quite enough to...

432
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:35,200
kind of divvy up
what they got way too much of.

433
00:42:39,800 --> 00:42:43,400
You're an odd one, aren't you, Jett?
But I like you.

434
00:42:51,600 --> 00:42:53,000
I like you, too.

435
00:42:54,800 --> 00:42:59,000
You're the best-looking gal
we've seen around here in a long time.

436
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:05,600
The prettiest one
I think I've seen down here.

437
00:43:06,200 --> 00:43:07,600
LESLIE: Thank you, Jett.

438
00:43:08,200 --> 00:43:10,000
That's a very nice compliment.

439
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:13,800
I'll tell my husband of that,
with your approval.

440
00:43:18,800 --> 00:43:20,800
No, I wouldn't do that.

441
00:43:24,600 --> 00:43:26,400
No, I wouldn't do that.

442
00:43:28,200 --> 00:43:29,600
[War Winds neighing]

443
00:44:00,800 --> 00:44:02,400
Beautiful Reata!

444
00:44:04,200 --> 00:44:06,400
Them's your neighbors live there.

445
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:09,400
Them kids there. Them's your ranch people.

446
00:44:10,600 --> 00:44:12,800
Those are Ángel Obregón's kids.

447
00:44:13,200 --> 00:44:15,400
That's the man who met us at the train.

448
00:44:17,400 --> 00:44:20,600
Sure in good shape, ain't they?
Whole bunch of them sick.

449
00:44:20,600 --> 00:44:22,200
What's the matter with them?

450
00:44:22,200 --> 00:44:25,000
JETT: I don't know. Just sick.
Every one of them.

451
00:44:27,400 --> 00:44:29,400
Wait a minute. I want to get out here.

452
00:44:29,400 --> 00:44:31,400
I wouldn't do that if I was you.

453
00:44:32,200 --> 00:44:33,400
Wait.

454
00:44:36,600 --> 00:44:39,400
You're the boss.
And you know it, don't you?

455
00:44:42,800 --> 00:44:44,000
LESLIE: May I come in?

456
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:52,600
<i>I'm Mrs. Benedict.</i>

457
00:44:53,800 --> 00:44:55,200
<i>Perdóname...</i>

458
00:44:56,000 --> 00:44:57,800
that I do not rise.

459
00:44:57,800 --> 00:45:00,400
[Baby crying]

460
00:45:01,400 --> 00:45:02,600
The baby is sick.

461
00:45:03,400 --> 00:45:05,000
My milk is not good.

462
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:36,400
[Gentle instrumental music]

463
00:45:49,400 --> 00:45:51,000
[War Winds whinnies]

464
00:45:59,600 --> 00:46:01,600
[Calls for help in Spanish]

465
00:46:20,400 --> 00:46:22,000
[Baby crying]

466
00:46:28,800 --> 00:46:30,400
LESLIE: Have you seen a doctor?

467
00:46:31,600 --> 00:46:34,800
Doctor? It is too far to come.

468
00:46:38,200 --> 00:46:41,600
JETT: Mrs. Leslie,
I think we'd better be getting on.

469
00:46:44,200 --> 00:46:46,000
This baby is extremely ill.

470
00:46:46,800 --> 00:46:48,600
JETT: You're not supposed to be in there.

471
00:46:50,400 --> 00:46:53,800
Try not to worry, Mrs. Obregón.
I'll be back soon.

472
00:46:55,800 --> 00:46:57,600
Bick's going to blow a gasket.

473
00:47:11,800 --> 00:47:13,000
LESLIE: What is it?

474
00:47:13,800 --> 00:47:15,600
<i>What's happened to him?</i>

475
00:47:16,800 --> 00:47:18,000
<i>What's wrong?</i>

476
00:47:33,600 --> 00:47:37,200
BICK: Where in the world have you been?
I've been looking for you, too.

477
00:47:38,600 --> 00:47:40,000
What happened to her?

478
00:47:41,200 --> 00:47:42,800
I stopped by the village.

479
00:47:43,800 --> 00:47:45,000
What happened?

480
00:47:45,400 --> 00:47:46,400
It's just awful.

481
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:51,200
I don't know. She was riding War Winds.

482
00:47:52,400 --> 00:47:54,600
She might have been thrown or something.

483
00:47:59,800 --> 00:48:01,400
What does the doctor say?

484
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:05,200
It's bad.

485
00:48:05,800 --> 00:48:08,000
<i>She hit her head on a mesquite stump.</i>

486
00:48:19,200 --> 00:48:21,400
She's been riding since she was six.

487
00:48:22,200 --> 00:48:25,800
She could ride anything.
And now this happens.

488
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:50,200
How is she?

489
00:48:50,600 --> 00:48:53,000
She's in a state of shock. Very serious.

490
00:48:53,400 --> 00:48:55,600
Concussion, possible hemorrhaging.

491
00:48:56,000 --> 00:48:57,400
I'm doing all I can do.

492
00:48:57,800 --> 00:49:00,200
I called Dr. Borneholm on the phone.

493
00:49:00,600 --> 00:49:02,600
<i>He'll be along any minute.</i>

494
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:24,000
Doctor.

495
00:50:18,200 --> 00:50:20,400
If only I hadn't bought that horse....

496
00:50:21,600 --> 00:50:23,600
Don't blame yourself, Jordan.

497
00:50:26,600 --> 00:50:29,200
If I hadn't, she'd be alive right now.

498
00:50:30,400 --> 00:50:31,800
Don't blame yourself.

499
00:50:33,600 --> 00:50:37,400
<i>This is a great misfortune,</i>
<i>but no one is to blame.</i>

500
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:43,200
<i>Things happen.</i>

501
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:02,000
-Mrs. Benedict, this is Dr. Borneholm.
-How do you do?

502
00:51:03,600 --> 00:51:05,600
DR. WALKER: I wish
I could've made it for Luz.

503
00:51:05,800 --> 00:51:08,800
DR. BORNEHOLM: Dr. Walker did
everything he could, I assure you.

504
00:51:13,400 --> 00:51:16,400
Dr. Walker, there's more for you to do,
I'm afraid.

505
00:51:17,200 --> 00:51:19,600
Mrs. Obregón's baby is very sick.

506
00:51:19,800 --> 00:51:24,200
His temperature must be at least 105.
Will you stop by, please?

507
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:26,200
Mrs. Obregón?

508
00:51:26,600 --> 00:51:28,200
In the village.

509
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:30,400
Jett will take you.

510
00:51:39,800 --> 00:51:42,200
I'll go with you myself, Doctor.

511
00:51:47,400 --> 00:51:48,600
What is this?

512
00:51:49,400 --> 00:51:51,000
You can't do that.

513
00:51:51,400 --> 00:51:52,800
He can't go there.

514
00:51:53,400 --> 00:51:54,800
He's our doctor.

515
00:51:55,800 --> 00:51:57,400
-Our doctor?
-Yes.

516
00:51:58,000 --> 00:51:59,800
You mean, the Benedicts' only?

517
00:51:59,800 --> 00:52:02,800
No, I mean, all of us.

518
00:52:04,200 --> 00:52:06,200
He doesn't tend those people.

519
00:52:08,600 --> 00:52:11,200
They have a way of doing things
by themselves.

520
00:52:13,600 --> 00:52:15,000
How did she get there?

521
00:52:15,600 --> 00:52:19,400
Now, don't go climbing on me.
I don't feel too good about it.

522
00:52:19,800 --> 00:52:23,000
Jordan, darling,
I don't think you quite understand.

523
00:52:23,600 --> 00:52:27,000
There's a child who's very sick.
I must take Dr. Walker.

524
00:52:28,800 --> 00:52:30,600
You'll go, won't you, Doctor?

525
00:52:33,200 --> 00:52:35,400
I'll be back just as soon as I can.

526
00:52:43,800 --> 00:52:47,200
[Melancholy instrumental music]

527
00:53:24,400 --> 00:53:26,200
BICK: I'm a lot better, honey.

528
00:53:28,400 --> 00:53:29,600
LESLIE: That's a good boy.

529
00:53:36,400 --> 00:53:38,000
<i>Where's my horse?</i>

530
00:53:42,800 --> 00:53:43,800
BICK: I shot him.

531
00:53:46,400 --> 00:53:47,800
<i>Bone was broken.</i>

532
00:53:49,400 --> 00:53:52,600
<i>Somebody had to do it.</i>
<i>I thought it'd be better if it was me.</i>

533
00:53:57,400 --> 00:53:58,400
BICK: The baby?

534
00:54:00,200 --> 00:54:03,000
LESLIE: He is alive, thanks to Dr. Walker.

535
00:54:08,800 --> 00:54:09,600
Good.

536
00:54:12,400 --> 00:54:14,400
[Organ music playing]

537
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:25,400
We need you in here for a few minutes
if you can break away.

538
00:54:27,400 --> 00:54:28,800
You're sure holding up fine.

539
00:54:28,800 --> 00:54:31,600
<i>In times like this</i>
<i>folks really show what they're made of...</i>

540
00:54:31,600 --> 00:54:33,600
<i>and you're sure holding up fine.</i>

541
00:54:42,800 --> 00:54:44,800
Vern and me thought a lot of Luz.

542
00:54:45,400 --> 00:54:47,200
I guess everybody did.

543
00:54:47,400 --> 00:54:49,000
At least everybody came.

544
00:54:49,200 --> 00:54:52,400
It's the biggest gathering for a funeral
I ever saw in Texas.

545
00:54:52,400 --> 00:54:54,600
It's a shame Luz wasn't here to enjoy it.

546
00:54:56,000 --> 00:54:59,200
I mean, she always did like
a big get-together.

547
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:01,800
She'd have had a fine time.

548
00:55:03,400 --> 00:55:05,600
-Come to see us.
-Thank you. Bye-bye.

549
00:55:05,600 --> 00:55:06,800
Come see us.

550
00:55:10,200 --> 00:55:13,600
I think you'll agree, your sister
was a very generous woman.

551
00:55:15,400 --> 00:55:19,000
<i>She wanted that boy</i>
<i>to have something worthwhile.</i>

552
00:55:20,200 --> 00:55:22,200
Now, that little piece of land is worth...

553
00:55:22,400 --> 00:55:24,600
$500, $600 at most.

554
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:29,800
I'm going to ask you, in reverence
to the memory of Luz Benedict...

555
00:55:30,600 --> 00:55:33,400
I'm going to ask you to give one Jett Rink...

556
00:55:34,200 --> 00:55:36,800
a check for twice the value of that land.

557
00:55:37,000 --> 00:55:39,400
<i>We can clean up the whole matter</i>
<i>right now.</i>

558
00:55:50,200 --> 00:55:52,000
BICK: Come inside, I want to talk to you.

559
00:55:52,200 --> 00:55:53,600
Just a minute, Bick.

560
00:55:54,600 --> 00:55:57,000
I'm afraid I'm going to beat you to it.

561
00:55:57,800 --> 00:55:58,800
I'm quitting.

562
00:55:59,800 --> 00:56:03,000
I lost the one friend I had in this place,
and I know it, too.

563
00:56:03,800 --> 00:56:07,000
So I quit, I dead quit.
You don't have to say another word to me.

564
00:56:07,400 --> 00:56:08,800
Nobody's firing you.

565
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:11,000
Boy, howdy, nobody's firing me.

566
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:13,200
I told you, I quit!

567
00:56:13,200 --> 00:56:14,800
Nobody wants to fire you.

568
00:56:16,200 --> 00:56:18,600
Come inside and listen
to what we have to say.

569
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:21,200
WHITESIDE: Come on in here, Jett.
Come on in, boy.

570
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:24,600
Hi, Jett. Nice to see you.

571
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:27,200
-Howdy, Jett. Good to see you.
-Howdy, Jett.

572
00:56:27,600 --> 00:56:30,800
BALE: Have my seat, boy. Sit right down.
You sure look good today.

573
00:56:31,600 --> 00:56:35,400
Sit down. I'm going to tell you about
a piece of luck that's come your way.

574
00:56:35,400 --> 00:56:38,400
WHITESIDE: Sit down, young man,
and make yourself comfortable.

575
00:56:39,200 --> 00:56:42,600
It's a real bad wind
that doesn't blow somebody some good.

576
00:56:45,800 --> 00:56:50,200
BICK: I don't have to tell you that Luz was
a woman of strong, sentimental feeling.

577
00:56:53,200 --> 00:56:57,400
She prepared a list of things she wanted
to give all the people on Reata.

578
00:56:57,800 --> 00:57:00,600
Yes. We find that she wanted to....

579
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:06,400
We find that her bequest to you was
in the nature of a little piece of ground.

580
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:10,800
BICK: It's the little piece we used to call
Buffalo Wallow.

581
00:57:16,400 --> 00:57:19,200
She wanted to give you something.
I know she did.

582
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:25,200
It's always been my aim to try
to keep Reata intact within the family.

583
00:57:27,600 --> 00:57:31,400
Now, that little piece is worth at most....
How much, Bale?

584
00:57:31,800 --> 00:57:34,600
BALE: At the most,
I'd say $500 or $600, Bick.

585
00:57:36,400 --> 00:57:39,400
Mr. Benedict, wanting to honor
his sister's wishes...

586
00:57:39,800 --> 00:57:43,600
and, of course, right along
with his own personal feeling for you....

587
00:57:44,200 --> 00:57:47,800
He wants to see to it that you get
something really worthwhile.

588
00:57:48,400 --> 00:57:51,200
Now, to get down to the point, Mr. Rink...

589
00:57:51,600 --> 00:57:55,200
we're prepared to place in your hands,
in cash...

590
00:57:55,800 --> 00:57:58,600
the sum of $1,200.

591
00:58:10,200 --> 00:58:11,600
$1,200...

592
00:58:12,200 --> 00:58:16,200
which, any of these gentlemen here
I'm sure will be happy to tell you...

593
00:58:16,200 --> 00:58:18,200
is twice the value of that land.

594
00:58:18,400 --> 00:58:22,000
PINKY: Definitely.
BALE: At least twice the value of that land.

595
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:39,800
PINKY: That's a lot of money.
What are you aiming do with all of it?

596
00:58:40,600 --> 00:58:42,400
BALE: You're in the chips now, boy.

597
00:58:43,400 --> 00:58:45,600
There it is. There it is, boy.

598
00:58:46,800 --> 00:58:48,400
And it's all yours.

599
00:58:56,400 --> 00:58:58,000
I don't know what to say.

600
00:59:01,800 --> 00:59:03,400
She sure was a fine lady.

601
00:59:03,400 --> 00:59:05,600
BALE: Yes, she was a fine lady. Hallelujah!

602
00:59:05,800 --> 00:59:06,800
PINKY: Amen.

603
00:59:15,200 --> 00:59:18,800
I want you to know
that I appreciate her generosity.

604
00:59:20,400 --> 00:59:22,600
Yours, too, Bick. And you all.

605
00:59:23,800 --> 00:59:25,400
I want to thank you for it.

606
00:59:29,400 --> 00:59:30,800
You know something, Bick?

607
00:59:32,600 --> 00:59:35,600
I don't know, but it might not be...

608
00:59:36,000 --> 00:59:39,800
a pretty good idea
to gamble along with old
<i>Madama.</i>

609
00:59:42,400 --> 00:59:43,600
How do you mean?

610
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:46,200
Just gamble on.

611
00:59:48,000 --> 00:59:49,600
Just keep what she gave me.

612
00:59:56,000 --> 00:59:58,000
I'm sentimental, too, Bick.

613
01:00:02,600 --> 01:00:06,200
I think it's good to gamble on with her.

614
01:00:08,600 --> 01:00:10,800
<i>I know that land ain't worth much...</i>

615
01:00:10,800 --> 01:00:14,800
but then someday I just might up...

616
01:00:15,400 --> 01:00:17,600
and put my own fence around her...

617
01:00:18,800 --> 01:00:20,800
and call her Little Reata.

618
01:00:26,800 --> 01:00:27,800
See you.

619
01:00:33,200 --> 01:00:37,200
There's one thing on earth more
important than money, and that's land!

620
01:00:37,200 --> 01:00:39,600
I heard Luz say it a thousand times.

621
01:00:39,800 --> 01:00:42,200
Pa said it and Bick, too. And it's true!

622
01:00:42,400 --> 01:00:45,600
If you ever get to Deep Smith,
you come and pay us a visit.

623
01:00:45,800 --> 01:00:47,800
We're just on the other side of Umbarger.

624
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:51,200
Only a little-bitty, no-account piece,
only we had a run of luck.

625
01:00:51,200 --> 01:00:54,400
-Only? Why, a gusher came in last year.
-How wonderful.

626
01:00:54,600 --> 01:00:56,800
Right now it's bringing in a million.

627
01:00:56,800 --> 01:00:59,000
-A million gallons?
-Dollars.

628
01:00:59,400 --> 01:01:01,000
A million dollars a year?

629
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:02,600
A million dollars a month.

630
01:01:04,600 --> 01:01:06,200
Goodbye. Thanks for treating us right.

631
01:01:06,400 --> 01:01:07,400
LESLIE: Thank you for coming.

632
01:01:09,400 --> 01:01:11,000
[Western instrumental music]

633
01:03:24,200 --> 01:03:26,200
[Organ music playing]

634
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:38,600
LESLIE: I just love talking to you,
Uncle Bawley.

635
01:03:40,400 --> 01:03:42,600
Now that it's over, you get your fellow...

636
01:03:42,800 --> 01:03:45,000
to take you around
and show you our country.

637
01:03:45,800 --> 01:03:49,000
See San Antonio, Dallas and Houston.

638
01:03:49,400 --> 01:03:52,800
I'm so impatient.
I want to see it all right now.

639
01:03:54,200 --> 01:03:58,000
You don't have to hurry, honey.
lt'll be here when you get around to it.

640
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:00,800
It's been here a long time.

641
01:04:02,200 --> 01:04:06,000
And when you've seen it all
and have lived with it as I have...

642
01:04:07,800 --> 01:04:11,600
in 25 years from now,
you'll feel about Texas just like I do.

643
01:04:12,600 --> 01:04:14,600
Twenty-five years from now!

644
01:04:15,200 --> 01:04:17,800
Twenty-five years from now
I'll be almost 50.

645
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:20,600
It's a nice age, Leslie.

646
01:04:21,600 --> 01:04:24,400
You'll see wonderful things in Texas
when you're 50.

647
01:04:26,800 --> 01:04:28,000
Perhaps.

648
01:04:29,400 --> 01:04:31,400
But I won't care as much then.

649
01:04:31,600 --> 01:04:32,800
You'll care more.

650
01:04:33,400 --> 01:04:36,800
<i>Because then you'll have been part of it all.</i>

651
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:38,800
BALE: Come on,
we need you in the powwow.

652
01:04:39,200 --> 01:04:40,400
BAWLEY: I'm coming, gentlemen.

653
01:04:49,400 --> 01:04:52,000
WHlTESlDE: You get with it, Gómez.
Get your people out.

654
01:04:52,400 --> 01:04:55,400
<i>I don't want any of them</i>
<i>sitting on their honkers come election day.</i>

655
01:04:55,600 --> 01:04:59,000
GOMEZ: Everything will be <i>bueno, señor</i>.
It will be the same: good.

656
01:05:09,200 --> 01:05:10,400
LESLIE: I love you.

657
01:05:13,400 --> 01:05:14,400
BICK: Thank you.

658
01:05:15,400 --> 01:05:17,800
<i>We're just talking business. Just business.</i>

659
01:05:19,400 --> 01:05:21,200
Please, don't mind me.

660
01:05:22,600 --> 01:05:23,600
Do go on.

661
01:05:25,800 --> 01:05:28,000
I'll listen, quiet as a little old mouse.

662
01:05:30,400 --> 01:05:32,000
You'd be bored, honey.

663
01:05:32,400 --> 01:05:33,600
This is dull.

664
01:05:34,400 --> 01:05:36,400
Why, I'd be fascinated.

665
01:05:39,200 --> 01:05:41,200
We're talking about politics.

666
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:45,800
You married me in Washington,
remember, darling?

667
01:05:46,400 --> 01:05:49,400
I lived next door to politics.
Brought up with it.

668
01:05:50,200 --> 01:05:52,600
Please go on talking. I'd love it.

669
01:05:54,000 --> 01:05:55,400
This is men's stuff.

670
01:05:56,400 --> 01:05:59,800
ADARENE: Leslie, how about a cup
of coffee or a drink?

671
01:06:03,800 --> 01:06:04,800
Men's stuff!

672
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:08,600
Lord have mercy!

673
01:06:10,600 --> 01:06:14,800
LESLIE: Set up my spinning wheel, girls.
I'll join the harem section in a minute.

674
01:06:16,400 --> 01:06:19,600
Don't you go worrying
your pretty little head about politics.

675
01:06:20,200 --> 01:06:23,000
LESLIE: You mean my pretty, empty head,
don't you, Judge?

676
01:06:26,200 --> 01:06:28,200
Could I get the coffee for you?

677
01:06:30,400 --> 01:06:32,800
You, too, Uncle Brutus?

678
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:37,000
You don't feel well, Leslie.

679
01:06:37,200 --> 01:06:39,400
LESLIE: I feel just great!

680
01:06:40,200 --> 01:06:42,800
<i>My adrenaline glands</i>
<i>are pumping beautifully.</i>

681
01:06:44,400 --> 01:06:45,400
Boo!

682
01:06:46,600 --> 01:06:49,000
LESLIE: If I may say so before retiring...

683
01:06:49,800 --> 01:06:52,800
you gentlemen date back 100,000 years.

684
01:06:54,200 --> 01:06:57,400
<i>You ought to be wearing leopard skins</i>
<i>and carrying clubs.</i>

685
01:06:57,600 --> 01:06:58,800
<i>Politics!</i>

686
01:06:59,200 --> 01:07:00,400
<i>Business!</i>

687
01:07:01,200 --> 01:07:05,000
What's so masculine about a conversation
that a woman can't enter into it?

688
01:07:07,600 --> 01:07:09,000
Leslie, you're tired.

689
01:07:13,200 --> 01:07:14,400
LESLIE: Perhaps I am.

690
01:07:31,400 --> 01:07:34,200
I reckon I'll go on upstairs
and get my beauty sleep.

691
01:07:34,600 --> 01:07:36,000
PINKY: You go ahead on, honey.

692
01:07:38,400 --> 01:07:40,000
VASHTI: Good night, gentlemen.

693
01:07:50,400 --> 01:07:51,600
That's right.

694
01:07:52,200 --> 01:07:55,600
Send the children on up to bed
so the grownups can talk.

695
01:07:59,800 --> 01:08:01,000
PINKY: Good night, honey.

696
01:08:36,400 --> 01:08:38,000
I must have dropped off.

697
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:44,600
Darling, I am sorry
about my caveman speech.

698
01:08:46,800 --> 01:08:49,800
I'll apologize to the others first thing,
I promise.

699
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:51,400
That's big of you.

700
01:08:52,000 --> 01:08:54,600
You certainly distinguished yourself
this evening.

701
01:08:54,800 --> 01:08:57,200
-Shh, they can hear.
-Hear? They heard you already.

702
01:08:57,400 --> 01:09:00,800
Every word you said out there.
We date back 100,000 years.

703
01:09:01,600 --> 01:09:04,200
I said I was sorry about the name-calling.

704
01:09:05,600 --> 01:09:07,400
It was very impolite, I know.

705
01:09:08,400 --> 01:09:11,000
But in principle, I was absolutely right.

706
01:09:11,200 --> 01:09:14,600
BICK: You come down here
and try to tell us how to run things.

707
01:09:14,600 --> 01:09:17,000
<i>Insulting my friends and everything.</i>

708
01:09:17,200 --> 01:09:19,200
Now you look here, Leslie.

709
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:22,600
<i>You're my wife, Mrs. Jordan Benedict.</i>

710
01:09:23,200 --> 01:09:27,400
<i>I'm asking you, when will you settle down</i>
<i>and behave like everybody else?</i>

711
01:09:28,800 --> 01:09:31,200
LESLIE: Never!
BICK: Who do you think you are, anyhow?

712
01:09:31,200 --> 01:09:33,000
[Yelling]
<i>Joan of Arc, or something?</i>

713
01:09:47,800 --> 01:09:50,000
LESLIE: Jordan, where are you going?

714
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:54,000
<i>Jordan, take off your hat.</i>

715
01:09:56,600 --> 01:09:58,800
Carrying on like Carrie Nation!

716
01:09:58,800 --> 01:10:01,800
Preaching stuff that's none
of your business, fixing the world.

717
01:10:01,800 --> 01:10:03,000
Why don't you join a club?

718
01:10:03,200 --> 01:10:06,400
Honestly, Jordan.
You make me sound just awful.

719
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:11,400
I'm not all that bad.

720
01:10:12,400 --> 01:10:15,200
You knew what a frightful girl I was
when you married me.

721
01:10:15,600 --> 01:10:17,800
<i>I did not deceive you, sir.</i>

722
01:10:18,600 --> 01:10:22,600
<i>From the first moment,</i>
<i>I couldn't have been more unpleasant.</i>

723
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:28,200
Anyway, you're stuck with me.

724
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:35,000
Yes, I guess.

725
01:10:38,000 --> 01:10:39,800
LESLIE: Honey, take your hat off.

726
01:10:53,400 --> 01:10:54,600
Besides...

727
01:10:55,400 --> 01:10:57,000
you love me very much.

728
01:11:03,800 --> 01:11:06,600
That fine mind of yours
gets pretty repulsive at times.

729
01:11:08,200 --> 01:11:10,400
That's not what you told me on the train.

730
01:11:12,400 --> 01:11:14,400
Now you're gonna throw that up to me.

731
01:11:15,200 --> 01:11:16,400
I thought what we....

732
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:20,600
I thought what we said on the train
was in confidence.

733
01:11:21,800 --> 01:11:23,600
LESLIE: Of course, darling.

734
01:11:25,200 --> 01:11:28,200
<i>But I'll never forget a single word</i>
<i>you say to me.</i>

735
01:11:29,200 --> 01:11:31,400
You can be pretty wonderful at times.

736
01:11:44,200 --> 01:11:45,400
Come on, partner.

737
01:11:46,400 --> 01:11:48,800
Why don't you kick off your spurs?

738
01:11:56,200 --> 01:11:58,200
[Inspirational instrumental music]

739
01:12:08,400 --> 01:12:11,600
LESLIE: What a glorious, gorgeous,
brand-new day!

740
01:12:13,600 --> 01:12:16,400
Let's spend every hour of it, just you and l.

741
01:12:16,600 --> 01:12:18,200
BICK: Honey, I'm beat.

742
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:19,800
Why?

743
01:12:21,600 --> 01:12:24,400
You have all the good things in the world.

744
01:12:24,600 --> 01:12:27,400
And a woman
who loves you very, very much.

745
01:12:36,800 --> 01:12:39,400
But that arguing takes a lot out of me.

746
01:12:45,000 --> 01:12:46,800
That was just frightful.

747
01:12:49,400 --> 01:12:52,000
<i>The best part about quarreling</i>
<i>is making up.</i>

748
01:12:53,800 --> 01:12:56,600
BICK: When we make up, we make up.
Don't we, honey?

749
01:12:59,600 --> 01:13:04,000
Why can't we take a trip, really see Texas?
Just let somebody else run Reata.

750
01:13:05,000 --> 01:13:06,200
Couldn't we?

751
01:13:08,200 --> 01:13:10,200
Honey, I want you to understand this.

752
01:13:10,800 --> 01:13:12,800
I run Reata at all times.

753
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:15,400
That's the way it is.

754
01:13:16,600 --> 01:13:19,000
Everything that's in it and on it
is run by me.

755
01:13:20,200 --> 01:13:21,400
Don't raise your voice.

756
01:13:21,400 --> 01:13:23,400
That's the way it's always been.

757
01:13:23,800 --> 01:13:27,000
Everything that has a Reata brand on it
is run by me.

758
01:13:29,600 --> 01:13:31,200
Does that include me?

759
01:13:33,400 --> 01:13:38,000
That's the way my father ran this outfit
and my grandfather, too. All of it.

760
01:13:38,600 --> 01:13:41,400
He kept it together for his son,
and my father for his.

761
01:13:41,600 --> 01:13:44,000
And I'm keeping it together for mine.

762
01:13:44,800 --> 01:13:46,400
All 595,000 square miles?

763
01:13:46,600 --> 01:13:48,000
All of it. For my son.

764
01:13:49,400 --> 01:13:51,400
You could at least say "our son."

765
01:13:52,400 --> 01:13:53,400
Our son.

766
01:13:55,200 --> 01:13:58,400
Don't you think that might be
a little too much for one little baby?

767
01:13:58,800 --> 01:14:00,400
Not if he's a Benedict.

768
01:14:05,600 --> 01:14:07,400
You'd better hope this is a boy.

769
01:14:10,400 --> 01:14:13,800
Our baby. I just said I'm hoping it's a boy.

770
01:14:16,000 --> 01:14:17,200
What do you mean?

771
01:14:18,200 --> 01:14:19,800
Why didn't you tell me?

772
01:14:21,400 --> 01:14:23,200
I'm telling you now.

773
01:14:27,200 --> 01:14:30,400
Why didn't you tell me?
I mean, I should know.

774
01:14:32,800 --> 01:14:34,400
-Are you sure?
-Sure.

775
01:14:36,600 --> 01:14:39,800
And our baby is going to be a boy.
I know it.

776
01:14:41,200 --> 01:14:43,400
A boy very much like his father.

777
01:14:47,600 --> 01:14:48,800
In many ways...

778
01:14:50,400 --> 01:14:51,600
but not all.

779
01:15:00,600 --> 01:15:02,600
Shouldn't she be putting on a little weight?

780
01:15:05,600 --> 01:15:09,200
It's natural, I think,
for him to be gaining faster.

781
01:15:10,200 --> 01:15:11,200
Let me see.

782
01:15:16,400 --> 01:15:17,600
Very heavy.

783
01:15:25,000 --> 01:15:26,200
LESLIE: Hello, sweetheart.

784
01:15:27,400 --> 01:15:29,000
He's building up fine.

785
01:15:30,400 --> 01:15:32,400
"l am now stronger than ever.

786
01:15:32,400 --> 01:15:35,800
"I'm helping a young Dr. Guerra
get started here.

787
01:15:36,600 --> 01:15:40,400
"Almost every day I find myself
walking three or four miles...

788
01:15:41,200 --> 01:15:45,600
<i>"through the dusty and dirty streets</i>
<i>of Vientecito village. "</i>

789
01:15:55,000 --> 01:15:57,000
Hello, Ángel. How are you?

790
01:15:57,600 --> 01:15:59,000
Good.

791
01:16:04,600 --> 01:16:07,400
I'd like to speak to Mr. Gómez, the boss.

792
01:16:07,600 --> 01:16:09,400
<i>The man that runs this place.</i>

793
01:16:09,400 --> 01:16:11,800
Mrs. Benedict, what is it I can do?

794
01:16:12,600 --> 01:16:15,800
Mr. Gómez, I'm going to leave
Dr. Guerra here with you.

795
01:16:16,200 --> 01:16:18,600
<i>He'll tell you things</i>
<i>that must be done immediately.</i>

796
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:20,600
This place is a scandal.

797
01:16:22,200 --> 01:16:25,000
Thank you, Dr. Guerra.
I'll get in touch with you.

798
01:16:25,000 --> 01:16:26,400
[Thanks her in Spanish]

799
01:16:28,200 --> 01:16:30,800
[Lighthearted instrumental music]

800
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:47,400
[Gunshot]

801
01:16:58,200 --> 01:16:59,200
LESLIE: Hello, Jett.

802
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:02,000
JETT: Howdy, Miss Leslie.
LESLIE: How are you?

803
01:17:03,400 --> 01:17:04,400
I'm doing good.

804
01:17:05,800 --> 01:17:08,400
LESLIE: You made some improvements.
JETT: Do you like it?

805
01:17:08,600 --> 01:17:09,600
LESLIE: It looks good.

806
01:17:16,400 --> 01:17:19,200
It ain't much yet, but it's coming along.

807
01:17:19,800 --> 01:17:21,600
LESLIE: I wouldn't have believed it.

808
01:17:21,600 --> 01:17:23,000
JETT: Believed what?

809
01:17:23,400 --> 01:17:27,400
LESLIE: Truthfully, I didn't expect this sort
of talent to be one of your virtues.

810
01:17:29,400 --> 01:17:32,800
JETT: That's the first time I was ever
accused of having any of that.

811
01:17:36,800 --> 01:17:39,800
It really is nice, Jett. Real nice.

812
01:17:41,200 --> 01:17:42,200
JETT: Someday...

813
01:17:42,400 --> 01:17:45,200
I'll have a place
that no one will be ashamed of.

814
01:17:54,400 --> 01:17:56,200
JETT: I cut them out of the newspaper.

815
01:17:56,200 --> 01:17:59,600
<i>I thought maybe they'd kind of</i>
<i>dress the place up a little bit.</i>

816
01:18:00,800 --> 01:18:01,600
LESLIE: Sweet of you.

817
01:18:12,200 --> 01:18:15,400
Do you want to come on in here,
sit down and rest a minute?

818
01:18:15,800 --> 01:18:16,600
LESLIE: Thank you.

819
01:18:27,200 --> 01:18:30,000
Having kids seems to agree with you,
you know?

820
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:33,200
You're looking prettier than ever.

821
01:18:34,600 --> 01:18:36,000
<i>Just as good, anyway.</i>

822
01:18:50,800 --> 01:18:52,600
My goodness, and tea!

823
01:18:53,200 --> 01:18:54,400
JETT: You like tea, don't you?

824
01:18:54,600 --> 01:18:58,200
I love it. It seems down here everybody
drinks gallons of coffee.

825
01:18:59,400 --> 01:19:00,400
JETT: I know.

826
01:19:17,400 --> 01:19:20,000
LESLIE: Mind if I pay you
a rather personal compliment?

827
01:19:23,400 --> 01:19:24,200
What is it?

828
01:19:25,200 --> 01:19:27,600
You make a very excellent cup of tea.

829
01:19:30,600 --> 01:19:33,000
I do a lot of things in a pinch.

830
01:19:39,000 --> 01:19:42,400
Do you like one lump or do you like two?

831
01:19:43,600 --> 01:19:45,400
LESLIE: I think I'll take mine straight.

832
01:19:46,400 --> 01:19:48,000
That's good enough for me.

833
01:19:52,200 --> 01:19:53,400
[Jett coughs]

834
01:19:56,400 --> 01:19:58,200
That's not too good, is it?

835
01:19:59,000 --> 01:20:01,000
When will you get married, Jett?

836
01:20:01,400 --> 01:20:05,400
Don't you need somebody to help you
with this kind of responsibility?

837
01:20:06,800 --> 01:20:10,400
When I get some time to look around,
I'll go back East and....

838
01:20:11,000 --> 01:20:13,200
To Maryland, places like that.

839
01:20:13,800 --> 01:20:18,000
You got any attractive sisters there that
might be interested in some poor people?

840
01:20:19,800 --> 01:20:21,600
Money isn't all, you know?

841
01:20:23,400 --> 01:20:25,200
Not when you've got it.

842
01:20:32,400 --> 01:20:34,400
The other people around here...

843
01:20:34,600 --> 01:20:37,400
why don't they help themselves
like you've done?

844
01:20:39,200 --> 01:20:42,600
When you say "other people,"
what do you mean?

845
01:20:46,800 --> 01:20:49,200
I've just come back from Vientecito.

846
01:20:49,800 --> 01:20:51,800
JETT: That bunch of wetbacks?

847
01:20:52,400 --> 01:20:55,200
You don't go mixing me up
with none of them.

848
01:20:56,000 --> 01:21:00,400
I'm just as much of Texas
as Bick Benedict is.

849
01:21:04,800 --> 01:21:06,800
JETT: I'm no wetback.
LESLIE: I know that.

850
01:21:09,200 --> 01:21:12,800
<i>You're very like Jordan in that respect.</i>
<i>Attitude, everything.</i>

851
01:21:14,000 --> 01:21:17,200
But your situation is so different.
You're a working man.

852
01:21:19,400 --> 01:21:21,800
That's something I'm gonna try to fix.

853
01:21:23,200 --> 01:21:24,800
Someday I will.

854
01:21:27,200 --> 01:21:28,400
All right, Gómez.

855
01:21:32,800 --> 01:21:34,200
Yes, I understand.

856
01:21:34,400 --> 01:21:35,800
Yes, thank you.

857
01:21:38,600 --> 01:21:40,600
LESLIE: Thanks for the tea party, Jett.

858
01:21:41,400 --> 01:21:43,400
And don't be such a stranger.

859
01:21:45,800 --> 01:21:47,600
<i>Stop by and pay us a visit.</i>

860
01:21:49,000 --> 01:21:50,600
I don't know about that.

861
01:21:50,600 --> 01:21:53,000
Bick's still got his kettle on for me.

862
01:22:12,400 --> 01:22:13,400
BICK: Leslie.

863
01:22:14,800 --> 01:22:16,200
Hello, darling.

864
01:22:18,200 --> 01:22:20,000
I was just having tea with Jett Rink.

865
01:22:20,200 --> 01:22:23,000
Gómez telephoned.
"Mrs. Benedict went to Vientecito.

866
01:22:23,400 --> 01:22:25,400
"I hope you're not displeased," he said.

867
01:22:25,600 --> 01:22:28,400
I've told you before....
What's this about Jett Rink?

868
01:22:28,800 --> 01:22:31,800
He made tea. Isn't that unbelievable?

869
01:22:32,600 --> 01:22:34,600
<i>He does so want to improve himself.</i>

870
01:22:36,200 --> 01:22:39,200
But your man Gómez, that camp he runs....

871
01:22:41,000 --> 01:22:42,000
It's hopeless.

872
01:22:42,000 --> 01:22:45,000
You can't go around this place
with no regard for who you are...

873
01:22:45,200 --> 01:22:46,800
interfering with those people.

874
01:22:47,200 --> 01:22:49,400
Jordan, that place is a scandal.

875
01:22:50,000 --> 01:22:52,200
Dr. Guerra threw his hands up in horror.

876
01:22:52,400 --> 01:22:54,000
That's his problem.

877
01:22:54,400 --> 01:22:57,600
You've been a powerful Texan for
100 years. Why don't you do something?

878
01:22:57,800 --> 01:22:59,800
I'm not the Red Cross, I'm a cow man.

879
01:22:59,800 --> 01:23:01,400
If you won't, I will.

880
01:23:01,400 --> 01:23:03,400
If you go near those dumps again...

881
01:23:03,400 --> 01:23:06,200
if I ever hear you get mixed up
in this migratory mess--

882
01:23:06,200 --> 01:23:07,600
LESLIE: What?
BICK: I'll leave you!

883
01:23:07,800 --> 01:23:10,000
BICK: That's what I'll do, I'll leave you!

884
01:23:13,800 --> 01:23:16,400
There's my darling little girl.

885
01:23:17,200 --> 01:23:21,400
Did you think your naughty mama was
never going to come up to see you?

886
01:23:22,000 --> 01:23:24,000
One thing you can be sure of:

887
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:27,400
One of these days I'll run
that Jett Rink's hide out of this country.

888
01:23:27,400 --> 01:23:30,400
[Enterprising instrumental music]

889
01:23:35,800 --> 01:23:38,800
[Soft instrumental music]

890
01:23:51,400 --> 01:23:54,000
BICK: Say hello to Luz. Say, "Hello, Luz."

891
01:23:54,200 --> 01:23:56,200
[Baby babbling]

892
01:23:57,000 --> 01:23:59,600
BICK: Look there. Say hello to little Luz.

893
01:24:03,400 --> 01:24:06,200
I don't care what you say.
She does look like Luz.

894
01:24:06,800 --> 01:24:08,200
Oh, honey.

895
01:24:09,800 --> 01:24:13,000
We're all gathered for the fourth
anniversary of my son's birth.

896
01:24:13,600 --> 01:24:15,000
LESLIE: And your daughter's.

897
01:24:17,400 --> 01:24:20,000
And I want to take
this auspicious occasion...

898
01:24:20,600 --> 01:24:23,000
to say that this young fellow here...

899
01:24:24,000 --> 01:24:26,600
is gonna grow up to be
one of Reata's top hands.

900
01:24:29,000 --> 01:24:31,400
I mean, this boy's gonna be the best.

901
01:24:33,000 --> 01:24:36,000
<i>Maybe he'll even grow up</i>
<i>to be better than his old man.</i>

902
01:24:36,600 --> 01:24:38,200
Girls, look at the pony.

903
01:24:45,400 --> 01:24:46,600
There he is, son.

904
01:24:47,200 --> 01:24:48,600
<i>He's all yours.</i>

905
01:24:49,200 --> 01:24:50,600
JORDAN: All mine, Daddy?

906
01:24:52,600 --> 01:24:53,600
[Jordan crying]

907
01:25:04,600 --> 01:25:05,800
JORDAN: No!

908
01:25:12,400 --> 01:25:13,800
Take him around, Ángel.

909
01:25:25,600 --> 01:25:27,000
Take it easy, son.

910
01:25:27,600 --> 01:25:28,800
He doesn't want to.

911
01:25:29,000 --> 01:25:30,800
I rode before I could walk.

912
01:25:32,000 --> 01:25:35,000
But that was you.
He's another person entirely.

913
01:25:35,400 --> 01:25:39,800
He is a Benedict. He's gonna stay
on that saddle if I have to tie him on.

914
01:25:57,200 --> 01:25:58,400
Take him away.

915
01:26:02,600 --> 01:26:04,200
POLO: No.
BICK: Let him ride, Polo.

916
01:26:05,400 --> 01:26:06,400
Let him ride.

917
01:26:16,400 --> 01:26:19,000
Take him up for his nap. I think he's tired.

918
01:26:30,800 --> 01:26:32,800
[Jordan crying]

919
01:26:56,800 --> 01:26:58,600
BICK: That wasn't so bad, was it, son?

920
01:27:21,400 --> 01:27:23,200
[Loud claps of thunder]

921
01:27:25,400 --> 01:27:29,400
BAWLEY: Bick knows everything about
running a ranch. Bone, hide and hair.

922
01:27:31,400 --> 01:27:33,600
He doesn't know a thing
about raising kids...

923
01:27:33,600 --> 01:27:35,400
any more than his father did.

924
01:27:35,800 --> 01:27:37,800
You just stay with it your way...

925
01:27:38,400 --> 01:27:41,800
and help those children grow up to be
what they want to be.

926
01:27:42,000 --> 01:27:44,200
I will, Uncle Bawley. I promise.

927
01:27:48,800 --> 01:27:50,800
PINKY: We're going to hit the hay.

928
01:27:54,800 --> 01:27:57,000
PINKY: Good night, Leslie.
LESLIE: Good night.

929
01:27:57,000 --> 01:28:01,400
PINKY: Good night.
BICK: Good night.

930
01:28:07,600 --> 01:28:09,200
It's time for me to turn in.

931
01:28:13,000 --> 01:28:16,200
-Good night, Bick.
-Good night, Bawley.

932
01:28:20,200 --> 01:28:23,600
VASHTI: Good night, everybody.
Don't forget to turn off the rain.

933
01:28:50,200 --> 01:28:51,400
Are you tired?

934
01:28:52,600 --> 01:28:53,600
LESLIE: No.

935
01:28:58,400 --> 01:29:01,800
<i>What's happening is we're getting</i>
<i>on each other's nerves.</i>

936
01:29:02,000 --> 01:29:03,000
Could be.

937
01:29:06,200 --> 01:29:09,600
LESLIE: We've been together
every day and night since we first met.

938
01:29:11,000 --> 01:29:12,200
Is that bad?

939
01:29:13,600 --> 01:29:14,600
LESLIE: No.

940
01:29:17,000 --> 01:29:19,600
<i>We're getting in the habit</i>
<i>of snapping at each other...</i>

941
01:29:23,000 --> 01:29:25,600
about things
we should've adjusted to years ago.

942
01:29:32,200 --> 01:29:36,800
<i>I think it would be a good idea</i>
<i>if I took the children home for a visit.</i>

943
01:29:38,200 --> 01:29:39,200
Home?

944
01:29:44,000 --> 01:29:45,400
If you're homesick....

945
01:29:46,400 --> 01:29:48,600
I mean, if that's the way you want it.

946
01:29:49,400 --> 01:29:52,200
LESLIE: That's not the way I want it.
BICK: All right, then.

947
01:29:57,600 --> 01:30:00,400
LESLIE: It'll be better for us
if we're apart for a while.

948
01:30:02,000 --> 01:30:03,800
<i>Better for us and the children.</i>

949
01:30:06,000 --> 01:30:09,000
<i>It'll give us both a chance</i>
<i>to think things over.</i>

950
01:30:18,800 --> 01:30:20,200
You know best, I guess.

951
01:30:22,000 --> 01:30:23,600
LESLIE: I think it will be best.

952
01:30:24,600 --> 01:30:27,600
[Tender instrumental music]

953
01:31:13,000 --> 01:31:14,400
LACEY: Hi.
DR. LYNNTON: 'Morning.

954
01:31:14,600 --> 01:31:16,200
Fine day for riding.

955
01:31:16,400 --> 01:31:17,800
Just magnificent.

956
01:31:20,200 --> 01:31:21,400
See you later.

957
01:31:24,400 --> 01:31:25,800
She's a lucky girl.

958
01:31:27,200 --> 01:31:30,400
If I had it to do again,
I'd still walk off with Jordan.

959
01:31:31,400 --> 01:31:33,200
Even if I knew it'd end like this.

960
01:31:35,600 --> 01:31:37,600
MRS. LYNNTON: You have no time
to be homesick...

961
01:31:37,600 --> 01:31:40,600
with this wedding and Thanksgiving
on us together.

962
01:31:43,800 --> 01:31:45,400
JORDAN: Pedro, come here.

963
01:31:49,000 --> 01:31:51,200
Pedro, eat your dinner like a good boy.

964
01:32:20,000 --> 01:32:24,600
DR. LYNNTON: Father, we bow our heads
in gratitude on this Thanksgiving Day.

965
01:32:25,600 --> 01:32:28,800
<i>We give thee humble and hearty thanks</i>
<i>for this, thy bounty...</i>

966
01:32:30,000 --> 01:32:32,400
beseeching thee to continue
thy loving kindness...

967
01:32:33,200 --> 01:32:38,000
that our land may still yield her increase,
to thy glory and our comfort.

968
01:32:38,600 --> 01:32:39,600
Amen.

969
01:32:45,000 --> 01:32:46,800
Is that Pedro?

970
01:32:47,800 --> 01:32:49,200
Yes, darling.

971
01:33:30,600 --> 01:33:32,800
LESLIE: It's a day
when we're supposed to be happy.

972
01:33:34,800 --> 01:33:36,400
Come on now, smile.

973
01:33:37,000 --> 01:33:38,200
Like Mommy.

974
01:33:47,400 --> 01:33:49,000
Is something wrong, Miss Leslie?

975
01:33:58,600 --> 01:34:00,600
Now maybe you'll stop crying.

976
01:34:01,400 --> 01:34:03,800
It's a message to you from your father.

977
01:34:04,400 --> 01:34:06,200
Is he gonna be here for dinner?

978
01:34:09,000 --> 01:34:09,800
No...

979
01:34:10,800 --> 01:34:14,600
but he says,
"I hope my darlings are all very happy.

980
01:34:15,600 --> 01:34:20,200
"I want them to know I miss them
very much and love each one very much."

981
01:34:36,000 --> 01:34:38,000
[Melancholy instrumental music]

982
01:35:02,200 --> 01:35:06,400
I could see you coming.
Why, Mr. Benedict, this is a good surprise!

983
01:35:08,200 --> 01:35:11,400
We're having a wedding.
Sure is plenty of excitement.

984
01:35:11,600 --> 01:35:13,400
[Organ playing bridal hymn]

985
01:36:15,400 --> 01:36:17,000
MINISTER: "Dearly beloved...

986
01:36:17,200 --> 01:36:21,600
"we are gathered here in the sight of God
and in the face of this company...

987
01:36:22,400 --> 01:36:26,600
"to join together this man
and this woman in holy matrimony...

988
01:36:27,400 --> 01:36:31,000
"which is an honorable estate
instituted of God.

989
01:36:32,200 --> 01:36:36,200
"David, wilt thou have this woman
for thy wedded wife?

990
01:36:36,400 --> 01:36:41,000
"To live together after God's ordinance
in the holiest state of matrimony?

991
01:36:41,400 --> 01:36:45,000
"Wilt thou love her, comfort her,
honor her...

992
01:36:45,400 --> 01:36:49,800
"and keep her in sickness and in health,
and forsaking all others...

993
01:36:50,800 --> 01:36:54,600
"keep thee only unto her
so long as you both shall live?"

994
01:36:55,600 --> 01:36:56,400
I will.

995
01:36:57,800 --> 01:37:01,000
MINISTER: "Lacey, wilt thou have this man
for thy wedded husband...

996
01:37:01,400 --> 01:37:05,800
"to live together after God's ordinance
in the holiest state of matrimony?

997
01:37:07,000 --> 01:37:10,600
<i>"Wilt thou love him, comfort him,</i>
<i>honor him...</i>

998
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:15,800
"and keep him in sickness and in health,
and forsaking all others...

999
01:37:16,600 --> 01:37:20,600
"keep thee only unto him
so long as you both shall live?"

1000
01:37:20,600 --> 01:37:21,600
LACEY: I will.

1001
01:37:22,000 --> 01:37:24,200
MINISTER: "Bless, O Lord, this ring...

1002
01:37:24,600 --> 01:37:29,200
"that he who gives it and she
who wears it may abide in thy peace...

1003
01:37:29,600 --> 01:37:33,600
"and continue in thy favor
unto their life's end.

1004
01:37:33,800 --> 01:37:34,800
<i>"Amen."</i>

1005
01:37:39,200 --> 01:37:41,200
DAVID: With this ring, I thee wed.

1006
01:37:43,800 --> 01:37:48,200
MINISTER: "Those whom God hath joined
together, let no man put asunder.

1007
01:37:49,400 --> 01:37:54,600
<i>"For as much as David and Lacey have</i>
<i>consented together in holy wedlock...</i>

1008
01:37:56,400 --> 01:37:59,800
"I pronounce that they are man and wife."

1009
01:38:19,800 --> 01:38:21,800
[Wedding music swells]

1010
01:38:31,600 --> 01:38:34,800
Are you ready to come back
to your old, beat-up cowhand?

1011
01:38:38,200 --> 01:38:40,600
I'm no different than I was when I left.

1012
01:38:42,200 --> 01:38:45,600
We Texans like a little vinegar
with our greens. It gives them flavor.

1013
01:38:48,200 --> 01:38:50,200
[Industrious instrumental music]

1014
01:39:15,400 --> 01:39:17,200
BICK: What do you think of old King Tut?

1015
01:39:17,200 --> 01:39:19,200
WHITESIDE: Boy, howdy,
that's some hunk of beef!

1016
01:39:19,400 --> 01:39:20,800
BICK: He's gonna make history, too.

1017
01:39:21,000 --> 01:39:24,200
When Bick finishes this breeding
program, he'll have an animal...

1018
01:39:24,600 --> 01:39:27,400
that's 99 percent beef
and the rest exaggeration.

1019
01:40:25,800 --> 01:40:28,400
Say, Ollie, do you see that?

1020
01:40:30,000 --> 01:40:31,600
That's Rink's truck.

1021
01:40:32,200 --> 01:40:34,200
BICK: I don't want him
hauling through my place.

1022
01:40:35,400 --> 01:40:39,200
Jett's got the easement, Bick.
He's got a right to go through the land.

1023
01:40:39,800 --> 01:40:41,400
No two ways about that.

1024
01:40:41,400 --> 01:40:44,000
I'm tired of his prospecting.
I want him out of here.

1025
01:40:44,000 --> 01:40:47,800
He's borrowed about all he could.
He's down to his last collar button.

1026
01:40:48,800 --> 01:40:50,000
Sure he is.

1027
01:40:51,400 --> 01:40:55,000
Buy him out, Ollie.
Buy him out and get him out of here.

1028
01:40:56,000 --> 01:40:57,600
[Loud rumbling]

1029
01:41:23,200 --> 01:41:25,200
[Joyous instrumental music]

1030
01:41:55,200 --> 01:41:56,800
Hello, Jett.

1031
01:41:56,800 --> 01:41:58,200
<i>What do you want?</i>

1032
01:42:08,800 --> 01:42:10,400
My well came in, Bick.

1033
01:42:13,800 --> 01:42:14,800
Fine.

1034
01:42:17,200 --> 01:42:18,800
That's wonderful, Jett.

1035
01:42:20,800 --> 01:42:22,600
Everybody thought I had a duster.

1036
01:42:23,400 --> 01:42:27,800
<i>You all thought Spindletop and</i>
<i>Burkburnett was all the oil there was.</i>

1037
01:42:28,600 --> 01:42:31,600
I'm here to tell you it ain't, boy. It's here.

1038
01:42:33,000 --> 01:42:35,600
There ain't a dang thing
you gonna do about it.

1039
01:42:35,800 --> 01:42:37,400
<i>My well came in big, so big.</i>

1040
01:42:38,000 --> 01:42:40,200
And there's more down there, bigger wells.

1041
01:42:46,200 --> 01:42:47,400
I'm rich, Bick!

1042
01:42:50,400 --> 01:42:53,600
I'm a rich one. I'm a rich boy.

1043
01:42:55,200 --> 01:42:58,600
I'm gonna have more money
than you ever thought you could have.

1044
01:42:58,800 --> 01:43:01,200
You and the rest of you
stinking sons of Benedicts.

1045
01:43:02,800 --> 01:43:05,600
Leslie, go into the house.
Take the women with you.

1046
01:43:06,200 --> 01:43:08,000
Jett, we're glad you struck oil.

1047
01:43:09,000 --> 01:43:10,600
Now, you go on along home.

1048
01:43:12,800 --> 01:43:15,400
My, you sure do look pretty, Miss Leslie.

1049
01:43:17,400 --> 01:43:19,200
You always did look pretty.

1050
01:43:20,600 --> 01:43:22,200
Pretty, good enough to eat.

1051
01:43:26,600 --> 01:43:28,000
Wait a minute.

1052
01:43:28,400 --> 01:43:30,000
Take it easy!

1053
01:43:34,000 --> 01:43:35,200
You're touchy, Bick.

1054
01:43:36,800 --> 01:43:38,400
Touchy as an old cook.

1055
01:43:42,200 --> 01:43:45,000
[Dramatic instrumental music]

1056
01:43:56,200 --> 01:43:59,000
BAWLEY: You should have shot him
a long time ago.

1057
01:43:59,000 --> 01:44:00,600
Now he's too rich to kill.